  "prompt": "What is the value of [math]\\sqrt [i\\pi ] {-1}[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\), we need to interpret the expression as taking \\((-1)\\) to the power of a complex number, \\(1/(i\\pi)\\). So, we are looking for:\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{1/(i\\pi)}\n\\]\n\nTo proceed, recall that \\(-1\\) can be expressed in the complex exponential form using Euler's formula:\n\n\\[\n-1 = e^{i\\pi + 2k\\pi i}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(k\\) is any integer, representing different branches of the complex logarithm. Hence, we have:\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{1/(i\\pi)} = \\left(e^{i\\pi + 2k\\pi i}\\right)^{1/(i\\pi)}\n\\]\n\nUsing the property of exponents, we get:\n\n\\[\n= e^{(i\\pi + 2k\\pi i)/(i\\pi)} = e^{1 + 2k}\n\\]\n\nThus, for different integer values of \\(k\\), the expression evaluates to:\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{1/(i\\pi)} = e \\cdot e^{2k}\n\\]\n\nSince \\(k\\) can be any integer, the general solution is \\(e \\cdot e^{2k}\\), where \\(e\\) is the base of the natural logarithm. The principal value (when \\(k=0\\)) is simply:\n\n\\[\ne\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the principal value of \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\) is \\(e\\).",
